notes:
## Why Manual Bilinear?
- GPU's built-in GL_LINEAR works on raw RGBA bytes
- Our data tiles encode float values as 16-bit integers in R,G channels
- Linear filtering on encoded bytes ≠ linear filtering on decoded values
- Solution: GL_NEAREST sampling + manual decode-then-interpolate in shader

## Shader Pattern
```glsl
// Sample 4 neighbors
vec4 tl = texture(u_dataTile, uv + vec2(-0.5, -0.5) / tileSize);
vec4 tr = texture(u_dataTile, uv + vec2(+0.5, -0.5) / tileSize);
vec4 bl = texture(u_dataTile, uv + vec2(-0.5, +0.5) / tileSize);
vec4 br = texture(u_dataTile, uv + vec2(+0.5, +0.5) / tileSize);
// Decode each
float vtl = decode(tl), vtr = decode(tr), vbl = decode(bl), vbr = decode(br);
// Bilinear mix
float value = mix(mix(vtl, vtr, fx), mix(vbl, vbr, fx), fy);
```

## Wind U/V Tiles
- Wind speed/direction requires separate U,V component tiles
- Can't interpolate speed+direction (polar coords) — must interpolate Cartesian U,V
- Reconstruct speed = sqrt(U^2+V^2), direction = atan2(V,U) after interpolation

## Files
- frontend/src/layers/shaders/weather.frag.glsl (bilinear decode)
- src/weatherman/tiling/router.py (U/V tile endpoint)
- src/weatherman/tiling/data_encoder.py (wind component extraction)

## Acceptance Criteria
- Smooth gradients with no visible pixel stepping
- Wind barbs/arrows point in physically correct interpolated directions
- No performance regression (< 1ms per tile render)

## Shader Implementation
```glsl
// Calculate texel coordinates and fractional parts
vec2 texelCoord = v_texCoord * tileSize - 0.5;
vec2 f = fract(texelCoord);
vec2 base = (floor(texelCoord) + 0.5) / tileSize;
vec2 step = 1.0 / tileSize;

// Sample 4 neighbors (GL_NEAREST)
float tl = decodeValue(texture(u_dataTile, base));
float tr = decodeValue(texture(u_dataTile, base + vec2(step.x, 0.0)));
float bl = decodeValue(texture(u_dataTile, base + vec2(0.0, step.y)));
float br = decodeValue(texture(u_dataTile, base + step));

// Bilinear mix
float value = mix(mix(tl, tr, f.x), mix(bl, br, f.x), f.y);
```

## Nodata Handling
- If any of the 4 neighbors is nodata, fall back to nearest valid
- Or: use nodata-aware interpolation with reduced weight

## Performance
- 4 texture lookups per fragment vs 1 — measure impact
- Should still be < 1ms per tile at 256x256

## Files
- frontend/src/layers/shaders/weather.frag.glsl (bilinear decode)

## Acceptance Criteria
- Smooth gradients, no visible pixel boundaries
- Correct values at tile edges (handle edge sampling)
- Performance within 2x of point sampling
- Nodata boundaries do not produce artifacts

## Shader Logic (weather.frag.glsl)
```glsl
uniform sampler2D u_dataTile;
uniform sampler2D u_colorRamp;  // 1D texture, 256 entries
uniform float u_valueMin;
uniform float u_valueMax;

// Decode 16-bit value from R,G channels
float decodeValue(vec4 texel) {
    if (texel.b > 0.5) return -1.0; // nodata flag
    return (texel.r + texel.g * 256.0) / 65535.0;
}

void main() {
    vec4 texel = texture(u_dataTile, v_texCoord);
    float normalized = decodeValue(texel);
    if (normalized < 0.0) { discard; } // nodata
    // Color ramp lookup
    vec4 color = texture(u_colorRamp, vec2(normalized, 0.5));
    gl_FragColor = color;
}
```

## Color Ramp Textures
- Generate 256x1 RGBA textures from existing colormap definitions in colormaps.py
- One texture per weather field (temperature, wind, pressure, waves)
- Upload as GL textures, switch via uniform when field changes
- Export color ramp data as JSON from Python for frontend consumption

## Files
- frontend/src/layers/shaders/weather.frag.glsl (implement)
- frontend/src/layers/shaders/weather.vert.glsl (geo-projection)
- frontend/src/layers/color-ramps.ts (new — generate GL textures from ramp data)
- src/weatherman/tiling/colormaps.py (export ramp data as JSON endpoint)

## Acceptance Criteria
- Visual output matches current TiTiler colored tiles (A/B comparison)
- Nodata areas are transparent
- Color ramp can be changed without re-fetching tiles
- Works for all weather fields

## Shader Changes (weather.frag.glsl)
```glsl
uniform sampler2D u_dataTileT0;
uniform sampler2D u_dataTileT1;
uniform float u_temporalMix; // 0.0 = T0, 1.0 = T1

void main() {
    float v0 = decodeValue(texture(u_dataTileT0, v_texCoord));
    float v1 = decodeValue(texture(u_dataTileT1, v_texCoord));
    // Handle nodata in either
    float value = (v0 < 0.0 || v1 < 0.0) ? max(v0, v1) : mix(v0, v1, u_temporalMix);
    vec4 color = texture(u_colorRamp, vec2(value, 0.5));
    gl_FragColor = color;
}
```

## TileManager Changes
- Load tiles for both T0 and T1 timesteps
- Prefetch T1 when approaching timestep boundary
- Bind both textures to separate texture units

## Animation Driver
- Sync u_temporalMix to timeline slider position
- Update every frame via requestAnimationFrame
- Reset to 0.0 when crossing timestep boundary

## Files
- frontend/src/layers/shaders/weather.frag.glsl (temporal blend)
- frontend/src/layers/TileManager.ts (dual-timestep loading)
- frontend/src/layers/WeatherGLLayer.ts (animation driver)

## Acceptance Criteria
- Smooth interpolation between forecast hours
- No visual discontinuity at timestep boundaries
- Physically plausible intermediate values
- Nodata handling does not create artifacts

description:
Update frontend/vite.config.ts to proxy /tiles, /health, and /metrics to the backend alongside the existing /api proxy.

WHY: The Vite dev server currently only proxies /api to http://localhost:8000. The frontend's useWeatherLayer hook constructs tile URLs at /tiles/... (relative, no host prefix), which means tile requests go to localhost:5173 (Vite) instead of localhost:8000 (backend). Without this proxy, tiles fail in development. The /health and /metrics proxies are optional but convenient for debugging from the browser.

CURRENT STATE (frontend/vite.config.ts):
  server: {
    proxy: {
      '/api': { target: 'http://localhost:8000', changeOrigin: true },
    },
  }

TARGET STATE:
  server: {
    proxy: {
      '/api': { target: 'http://localhost:8000', changeOrigin: true },
      '/tiles': { target: 'http://localhost:8000', changeOrigin: true },
      '/health': { target: 'http://localhost:8000', changeOrigin: true },
      '/metrics': { target: 'http://localhost:8000', changeOrigin: true },
    },
  }

NOTES:
- This only affects the Vite dev server — production builds use VITE_API_BASE_URL or a reverse proxy
- The frontend .env and .env.example both set VITE_API_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8000, but the useWeatherLayer hook constructs URLs as {apiBase}/tiles/... where apiBase defaults to '' (empty string) if VITE_API_BASE_URL is not set. The Vite proxy handles this case.
- changeOrigin: true ensures the Host header is rewritten, which some backend frameworks require

FILE: frontend/vite.config.ts
